items.name: Acorn Is Spinning
items.description:
AcornXL V1

This is my first XL model. It's definitely not perfect as there just isn't a lot to work with yet for SDXL. It is pretty good though. I use a mixture of samplers, but so far my favorites are DPM++ 2M Karras and DPM++ SDE Karras. Normally CFGs from 4.5 to 7. Steps between 20 and 40. I have experimented using it together with the base SDXL refiner and so far it seems to improve results. If you use the up to date version of Automatic1111 it allows you to have the refiner kick it at whatever percentage you want. Some of my example pic use it starting at 50% up to 90%. Just use some trial and error and see what works for you.

AND as always, my sample images use NO loras, textual inversions or negative TIs. Model and webui extensions only.

sdxl_vae is baked in

Feel free to post your gens down below. As always, I love to see what you make.

Acorn Photo Diversity V5

After releasing my Diversity V4 of the Acorn Photo models, I wasn't quite happy with the photo quality level. I kept testing and I believe this new version does a better job.

Prompting is different with this version. No longer is the (photorealistic) prompt needed and overall you often need less prompting and less negative prompts. As always, my sample images contain no Loras or TIs, either positive or negative.

Samplers I use mostly DPM++ 2M Karras and DPM++ 3M SDE Karras although many work fine, these are my favorites.

CFG anything from 6 down to 2 work good. I have found that if facial expression are too strong at 5 or 6, running it again at 2.5 or 3 still generates a great image but tones down exaggerated stuff.

Steps are usually 20 to 30.

vae-ft-mse-840000-ema-pruned baked in to all 1.5 models of the Acorn Series

Acorn Photo Diversity V4

Updated to generate a greater range of ethnicities.

If you would like to support me: https://bmc.link/aerreth2eL

I use DPM++ 2M Karras mostly, but also DPM++ SDE Karras and DPM++ 2M SDE Karras. CFGs from 4 to 6 mostly but depending on preference it doesn't get bad well up to 10.

Post your creations down below. I would love to see what you make.

Acorn Photo V2

This model increases the photo realism significantly over the previous version while still being a very versatile model. It is great for portrait type people pics but also for more action oriented things like Fantasy RPG type shots.

If you would like to support me: https://bmc.link/aerreth2eL

Post your creations down below. I would love to see what you make.

My goal is to get a model that is versatile enough to generate any kind of content equally well. To date, this is the most photorealistic model I have made. Acorn Is Spinning seems slighty more versitile in what it will do, but Acorn Photo seems to be a little better at just pure photos of people.

What I can say is that in using a lot of models, this merge has given me the best results I have achieved.

My true goal is to get a model that is versatile enough to generate any kind of content equally well. modelVersions.description:
I have a buy me a coffee page if you would like to support me: https://bmc.link/aerreth2eL

My goal is to get a model that is versatile enough to generate any kind of content equally well. To date, this is the most photorealistic model I have made. Acorn Is Spinning seems slightly more versatile in what it will do, but Acorn Photo seems to be a little better at just pure photos of people.

Recommend to use (photorealistic:1.4) in the prompt. Also 1.5 or 1.6 work well.

Recommended negative: anime, cartoon, paintings, glossy skin, (large areolas), (worst quality:2), (low quality:2), ((monochrome)), ((grayscale)), (skin tags:1.5), skin spots, acne, skin blemishes, Watermark, Text, deformed, disfigured, poorly drawn face, mutated, extra limb, poorly drawn hands, missing limb, floating limbs, disconnected limbs, disconnected head, malformed hands, long neck, mutated hands and fingers, bad hands, missing fingers, cropped, huge calf, fused hand

This is not a replacement of Acorn Is Spinning, but an addition with a little different use case. Feel free to play with both and see what you can make. Please post any examples you like as well.

The examples I upload to demonstrate the model are done with no Lora, Textual Inversions or Lycos. Nothing but the prompts and upscales.

I can't accurately state exactly what is in the mix or how much weight each has as there has been a lot of trial and error. The list of models included that I am sure about are:

Photon_v10

Aamon_v10

Colorful_v31

ConsistentFactor_euclidV51

AlmostHumanMix_v10r

EroticVision_v4

NextPhoto_v20

LOFI

QGOPromptingreal_qgo10a

There might be a few other in the mix, but the heaviest weight started with Photon. On it's own, it seems to be about the best single model I have found but mixing in some of the others made some big improvements to the overall outputs and versatility.

I can take no credit for creation, so if you like the model, enjoy it and mix in other new stuff and make it better.

I get the best results with CFGs from 4.5 to 6, with DPM++ 2S a Karras and DPM++ 2M Karras. Normally around 25 to 27 steps although more steps is rarely a bad thing, just takes longer. Best to use the highest resolution you can as well. I do a lot at 1024 X 768 as well as 768 X 768, 768 X 976 and recently started using the the ADetailer instead of the Restore Faces.

For Clip Skips, I have gotten some great results with all of them up to 12, but the best are probably 1,2,3 and 6 most of the time. It seems to get nice results all the way up, but the higher you go, the farther it gets from the prompt while still giving pleasing images. Just maybe not the one you were looking for.

items.name: Billions of Charaters - attires, ethnics, poses, paterns, expressions, makeups, hair, accesoires, bodyshapes, ages
items.description:
I got hyped a bit and created tons of lists for unique character creations. You've got billions of possibilities. However, I realized that mainting such a huge set is a pain in the ass. Luckily I found a useful information at the dynamic prompts GIT-page. You can use YAML-files. :D From here on it become awesome. Instead of 100 files you get 1 file with all the possibilties and I can maintain it more easily. I'll add a section to my guide.

Don't forget to leave a ‚ù§Ô∏è to get a notification for future updates. ‚≠ê reviews are appreciated, too. Let me see what you created with this tool. ;)

If you want to contribute an extension, check the guide linked below.

note: Yaml files will throw isseus when using: "a1111-sd-webui-tagcomplete"extension. That's related to the extension, not the wildcards.

Usage

Unleash the full power: 

Activate: Dynamic Prompts->Advanced Options->Unlink seed from prompt

Usage is pretty much the same as for "regular" wildcards.

You need the SD Dynamic Prompt Extension. Put the files directly into the wildcard folder:

~\stable-diffusion-webui\extensions\sd-dynamic-prompts\wildcards

They show up as a menu on the left in the Wildcards tab.

The YAML is structured and indented (that's how they work). Just with a little difference. You have to add the category layers in the wildcard.

Example for a female character:

__BoChars/female/modern__

A cool thing you can do, too, is using a wildcard "*" in the wildcards. So you could use the magical chararcter wildcards in the same prompt and get chars from both sets:

__BoChars*/female/modern__
__clothings*__ # for clothings from both sets

I made those easy to use cards for charcater creations. There are some wildcards that are not used for it. Have a look what's in there, too. You'll find a full list below. (another nice part of YAMLs)

You are welcome

Leave a star review, if you like it. so other can find those awesome cards more easily.

I plan to add more themes as extensions in the future. SDXL is coming, and wildcards are limitless.

If you want to support me, feel free to buy me a coffee. ;)

I plan to do some more subsets for different themes (like my magical characters). They'll be extensions to this base wildcards.

Keep in mind, that those are only wildcards. Your model might not have learned all of the items.

You can use wildcards with the Dynamic Prompts extension. Use the filename with 2 underscores in front and in the back __filename__ in your prompts.

Have experimenting with it.

items.name: Harak
items.description:
This is a Hypernetwork based off of a character from an episode of Conan the Barbarian, called An Evil Wind in Kunark. He is based off of an obscure deity from the Stygian pantheon from the Conan the Barbarian novels. He is based loosely on Horus. Depending where you go or look, the name Harak is also shown to be spelled Harakt and Harakht. While known as a falcon or hawk God, the cartoon shows Harak as being a mix of an eagle, hawk, and perhaps even a vulture. Also, he is portrayed as a demon and not a God.

The first Hypernetwork was made with screenshots I made back in 2006 when Youtube was new. The images had to be scaled and cropped to make them work.

The Hypernetwork works well on a weight of 0.85. It works well on other weights as well, though I consider 0.85 to be the better of the weights. For image making, the usual default settings work well.

items.name: Norman Timbs Special (1948)
items.description:
Support needed ! Out of colab credits. You can support me here to be able to render better models (https://ko-fi.com/djo226). Supporters can request model.

You can also subscribe to my Patreon and get exclusive models (Request, ...).

The Norman Timbs Special is a homebuilt Sport Custom built by Norman Timbs over a span of three years. Norman's streamlined custom was supposed to be a prototype for a limited series of cars reflecting advanced concepts in performance and aesthetics. Norman handmade an aluminum body for the car by forming panels on the wooden pattern. The panels were then welded together.The chassis was made of welded aircraft tubing. It was powered by a 1948 Buick Straight 8 engine located just behind the driver's seat. The rear body on the car was hinged to raise hydraulically for access to the engine compartment, fuel tank and spare tire. The fuel tank was placed between the wheels. The front hood covered a luggage compartment. In the rear, taillights from a 1939 Ford were installed. Total cost of the build was $10,000 according to Mechanix Illustrated September 1949.

In 1954 the Norman's Buick Special was featured in Motor Life February 1954. By then the car had been painted white. it was currently owned by Air Force Officer Jim Davis of Manhattan Beach, California. The article stated that the car was the brain-child of former aircraft manufacturer Larry Timm. According to the story Larry designed and built the car over a three year period ending in 1948. Davis bought the car in 1952 and was, according to the story, the first person to have the car registered for road use. Norman's Buick Special was featured in an episode of Buck Rogers.

Colour: Black

Introduction:

This is a fishnet effect LORA, which will produce a fishnet-like effect on clothing, which will affect both legs and clothing. The mesh under low weight will be relatively small, and under high weight, it will be larger, and at the same time, it will have a certain impact on the clothing.

Don't be fooled by the small size of this LORA!

The characteristics of this LORA are as follows:

1. Elaborately crafted using the differential extraction method, so the volume is small. In addition to affecting the texture of stockings, it has little effect on other content of the picture.

2. All photos are taken with real-life high-definition cameras to ensure real effects.

3. Because it has less impact on other content of the screen, it doesn't matter even if the weight is turned on a lot.

Why do you have to make another one when you already have so many stockings LORA?

because I found:

1. The existing LORA will cause some pollution to the picture. Either it is clothes, or it is shoes, can you make a LORA, which will only affect the texture of stockings and not affect other screen content?

2. The existing LORA does not subdivide the thickness and style of stockings, and the overall situation is rather chaotic.

So I made this LORA, and later I will make a series of LORAs with different thicknesses and textures, all of which are made of real-life materials and made using the difference extraction method to ensure the quality.

So this might be the best HISI LORA you've ever used.

The actual test found that this LORA works well on various models. But I haven't fully tested it yet, I hope you can give me more pictures, if you encounter any problems, please leave a message.

The weight can be between 0 and 1.2 and needs to be set according to actual needs.

items.name: Jill St.John (1970-79 era - CHECKPOINT)
items.description:
THERE IS A LORA VERSION OF THIS MODEL AVAILABLE. IT IS EXACTLY THE SAME MODEL AS THIS ONE, EXCEPT IN A DIFFERENT AND LIGHTER FORMAT.

Shivam Dreambooth of American actress Jill St.John, using 277 ref images and 1400 (real) reg images, for 15,000 steps.

The period covered is around 1970-1976. To get a generation of the younger version, put the word young in front of the key prompt, and use brackets or other weighting methods to control the degree of youth.

I generally use these models in complex workflows, inpainting faces after initial T2Is, and using ControlNet extensively. So if you're hoping for one-click prompt magic, my models aren't data-curated with this in mind, but rather as tools for traditional workflows that use Photoshop and other older methods.

This model may well produce subject-accurate NSFW output unless countered in negative prompts.
